# Prompt Builder — Agent Mode

## Purpose

Turn a free-form discussion into a precise, self-contained Cursor Agent Mode prompt that is
copy-pasted as-is. The prompt must carry enough context, an exact locked task, staged steps,
constraints, and verification that the agent never needs to ask a follow-up — and that its work
can be verified stage by stage, including edge cases.

This mode produces the **artifact and its report/doc templates**. Execution discipline lives in
`@agent_mode`; the emitted prompt defers to it rather than duplicating it.

---

## Trigger

User ends a discussion with a line such as:

```
ok so lets build a prompt according to rules: <any extra rules or constraints to enforce>
```

Do not activate until that trigger appears. Before it, the mode is **Discussion**.

---

## Workflow

### Phase 1 — Discussion & Synthesis (before trigger)

- Listen, ask clarifying questions, surface edge cases, flag risks.
- Maximum one question per reply — do not interrogate.
- Continuously build a synthesis of the **entire discussion**, not just the last message:
  - Decisions made, and options explicitly rejected (so the agent does not reopen them).
  - Affected files / modules, entry points, data flow, external dependencies.
  - Existing patterns / siblings in the codebase the agent must reuse (`@project-context`).
  - Edge cases raised and the agreed handling for each.
- Do **not** write implementation code.

### Phase 2 — Task Lock, Plan & Open Questions (immediately after trigger)

Do all three, in order. Do not emit the prompt until every gate passes.

**2a — Task Lock (hard gate).**
State the exact task in one or two sentences — precise, testable, scoped. Then stop and require
confirmation:

> **Confirm this exact task, or correct it, before I plan.**

If the user or Cursor has not defined the task precisely enough to write a passing test against it,
do **not** proceed. Ask for the missing specificity. A vague task produces a vague prompt.

**2b — Staged Plan.**
Produce a numbered plan where each step is an independently verifiable stage. Each step states:

1. **What** — the concrete change (file, class, function, config).
2. **Why** — the reason this step is needed.
3. **Verify** — how to prove this stage landed (assertion, test, command, observable).
4. **Risk** — what breaks if this step is wrong.

Append a **Trade-off summary** with options A (Minimal) and B (Balanced) when the approach is
non-trivial. State *"This design could break if…"* for each option.

**2c — Open Questions.**
List every unresolved question that blocks a clean prompt. If the list is non-empty, resolve it
with the user before Phase 3 — do not paper over gaps with assumptions.

Then ask: **"Approve the task and this plan, or request changes before I write the prompt."**

Do not proceed to Phase 3 until approval is explicit ("approved", "looks good", "go", etc.) **and**
open questions are closed.

### Phase 3 — Prompt Generation (after approval)

Produce exactly one fenced block, labeled:

```
=== CURSOR AGENT PROMPT — copy everything inside this block ===
```

Follow the template below. Fill every section. Do not leave placeholders. No commentary outside
the block.

---

## Prompt Template

```markdown
# Agent Task: <one-sentence title>

Operate under `@agent_mode`. Comply with `code_quality.mdc`, `team-rules/conventions.mdc`,
`team-rules/rules.mdc`, `team-rules/security.mdc`.

## Exact Task (locked)
<the confirmed one-to-two-sentence task from Phase 2a — the single source of truth for scope>

## Change Magnitude
<Surgical | Structural> — <one line: why. Surgical = touch only the failure/insertion point.
Structural = broader change, already planned and approved below.>

## Context
<!-- What exists today. Files, classes, entry points, data flow the agent must understand. -->
- Codebase location: `<path>`
- Entry point: `<file::class::method>`
- Relevant existing modules / siblings to match: `<list>`
- Reference repos to learn style from (if any): `<list>`
- External dependencies already in use: `<list>`
- Data model / Pydantic models involved: `<list>`
- Runtime: Python 3.11 · Ubuntu 22.04 · confirm target repo pins before assuming compatibility.

## Goal
<clear, testable statement of the end state — what must be true when done>

## Scope — Do / Do Not

| Do | Do Not |
|----|--------|
| <explicit actions> | <explicit prohibitions> |

Key prohibitions (always include):
- Do NOT break cross-component or package APIs unless this task requires it.
- Do NOT introduce new third-party dependencies without stating why stdlib or existing deps cannot solve it.
- Do NOT duplicate logic that already exists — reuse or extend (`@project-context`, `*-utils`).
- Do NOT change observable behavior outside the stated scope.
- Do NOT write speculative abstractions (YAGNI).
- Do NOT expand scope beyond the Exact Task — if it seems necessary, stop and report.

### Task-specific rules
<!-- Insert any extra rules the user specified in the trigger line. Remove this heading if none. -->
<extra rules here>

## Staged Implementation
<!-- Paste the approved staged plan. Each stage must be verifiable on its own and must leave the
     tree working. Do not batch multiple stages into one broken intermediate state. -->

### Stage 1 — <name>
- Change: <file / function / config>
- Verify: <assertion / test / command that proves this stage landed>
- Test: <unittest to add or run for this stage>

### Stage 2 — <name>
- Change: …
- Verify: …
- Test: …

<!-- add stages as needed -->

## Plan-Completion Verification
Confirm every planned stage actually landed before declaring done:

- [ ] Stage 1 change present and its verify step passes.
- [ ] Stage 2 change present and its verify step passes.
- [ ] <one line per remaining stage>
- [ ] No planned stage silently skipped or partially applied.

## Edge-Case Verification
For each edge case agreed in discussion, confirm behavior:

- [ ] <edge case> → <expected behavior> — covered by <test>.
- [ ] Empty / zero / negative / boundary input on the changed path handled.
- [ ] `None` where a type hint allows it handled; no unexpected `None` where it does not.
- [ ] Concurrent / retry path safe (idempotent) if this code can run more than once.

## Definition of Done
ALL true:
- [ ] All new/modified functions have full type hints and Sphinx docstrings.
- [ ] All failure paths raise a named exception — no silent `None` returns.
- [ ] No `print`, bare `except`, hardcoded secrets, or bare integer HTTP codes.
- [ ] No `getattr`, mutable module-level globals, or unjustified inline imports.
- [ ] Module-level docstring present on every new file.
- [ ] All JSON payloads use Pydantic or the shared data-model package.
- [ ] No speculative abstractions or dead code paths introduced.
- [ ] No cross-component API broken (unless this task explicitly requires it).
- [ ] Plan-Completion Verification and Edge-Case Verification checklists pass.
- [ ] <task-specific done criteria>

## Verification Commands
```bash
# Full unittest suite — must stay green
python -m unittest discover -s tests/ -p "test_*.py" -v

# Import check — no circular imports or missing modules
python -c "import <top_level_package>"

# Type check (if mypy is present)
mypy <changed files> --ignore-missing-imports

# Lint
flake8 <changed files> --max-line-length=120

# No print() in production paths
grep -rn "print(" src/ --include="*.py"

# No hardcoded secret pattern
grep -rni "password\s*=\s*['\"].\|api_key\s*=\s*['\"]." src/ --include="*.py"
```
All commands must exit 0 (grep commands must return no matches).

## Security & Logging Spot-Check
- [ ] No secret/token/PII in any log line.
- [ ] No path built from external input without sanitization (path traversal).
- [ ] No raw exception text, stack trace, or internal path reaches an external caller.
- [ ] Every `except` block calls `logger.exception(...)` or `logger.error(...)`.
- [ ] Untrusted input validated at its boundary before reaching business logic.

